    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, originalism is a judicial philosophy that interprets the U.S. Constitution based on the understood meaning at the time it was framed. Proponents argue that it ensures a more stable and predictable legal system by adhering to the original intent of the Constitution's framers. They believe that this method prevents judges from imposing their own personal views and constraints judicial activism. However, critics argue that it can be rigid and dismissive of evolving societal values and norms.",
